# Template for recommendation.yaml -- describes the specific change you're about
# to make (or just made) in THIS repo, so `make check` (SecEng-VSCodeAgent's
# evaluate command) challenges something real instead of falling back to
# SecEng-DevilsAdvocate's shared examples/recommendation.yaml.
#
# Copy this file to recommendation.yaml (gitignored -- it's a per-change working
# draft, not durable history; the durable record is your DESIGN_DECISIONS.md
# entry) and fill it in before running `make check`.
#
# Only these five fields are actually read by DevilsAdvocate's challenge command
# (src/seceng_devils_advocate/cli.py): id, claims, assumptions, evidence,
# alternatives. Everything else here is for a human reading the file, not
# consumed by the tool.
#
# Verdict logic (see SecEng-DevilsAdvocate/src/seceng_devils_advocate/challenge.py):
# a claim only counts as "supported" if it appears verbatim (exact string match)
# in evidence[].claim with a non-empty evidence[].source. Unsupported claims push
# the verdict toward conditional-pass/fail, scaled by this repo's own risk_tier
# (see mission.yaml) -- higher risk_tier tolerates fewer unsupported claims.

id: rec-CHANGE-NAME-YYYY-MM-DD

title: One-line description of the change

claims:
  # Assertions you're making about why this change is good/safe/correct.
  # Each one you can actually back up should have a matching entry in evidence[]
  # below with the EXACT SAME TEXT.
  - Claim one, stated as a factual assertion
  - Claim two

assumptions:
  # Things you're taking for granted that aren't independently verified here.
  - Assumption one

evidence:
  # One entry per claim you can support. "source" must be non-empty for the
  # claim to count as supported -- a real command output, CI run, test result,
  # or file/line reference, not a vague restatement of the claim.
  - claim: Claim one, stated as a factual assertion
    source: "e.g. `make test` output, a CI run URL, or a specific file/line"
    confidence: high

alternatives:
  # What else you considered and didn't do, even briefly.
  - Alternative approach (rejected because ...)
